                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">Nations are competing for strategic locations on the Moon...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Devansh Singh Rawal</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 27, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-devansh.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>In a move signaling a new era of cosmic contention, multiple nations have laid out ambitious plans for permanent lunar bases. The focus is not on planting flags, but on the strategic control of resources, particularly water ice discovered in the permanently shadowed craters of the lunar poles. This ice is seen as the key to a sustainable presence in space, as it can be converted into water, oxygen, and rocket fuel.</p>
                                <blockquote>"We are not just going back to the Moon; we are going to stay. And what we find there will define humanity's future in space for the next century."</blockquote>
                                <p>The technological and economic stakes are immense. The nation or coalition that first masters in-situ resource utilization (ISRU) will have a decisive advantage, capable of building and refueling spacecraft far beyond Earth's deep gravity well. This could pave the way for missions to Mars and beyond, making the Moon the strategic high ground of the 21st century.</p>
