                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="images/geo2.avif" alt="Geopolitics Article 2" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-purple-700 mb-2">Geopolitics</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Arctic Shipping Lanes Open: A New Arena for Superpower Rivalry</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">As polar ice melts, new trade routes emerge, sparking a geopolitical chess match...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Jane Doe</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 22, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-jane.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>For centuries, the Arctic was an impassable frozen wasteland. But climate change is redrawing the map. As polar ice recedes at an alarming rate, the Northern Sea Route is emerging as a viable and much shorter shipping lane between Europe and Asia. This has not gone unnoticed by the world's great powers.</p>
                                <p>Russia is heavily investing in icebreaker fleets and military bases to control this new artery of global trade. China, styling itself as a "near-Arctic state," is seeking to integrate the route into its Belt and Road Initiative. Meanwhile, the United States and Canada are scrambling to assert their sovereignty and ensure freedom of navigation.</p>
                                <blockquote>"The Arctic is the new Suez Canal, but with far greater military and environmental implications. Control of these waters will be a defining feature of 21st-century geopolitics."</blockquote>
                                <p>At stake is not just control over shipping lanes, but access to vast, untapped reserves of oil, gas, and rare earth minerals. The thawing of the Arctic is setting the stage for a new cold war, fought this time on ice and water.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- EHS Page Section -->
                <section id="page-ehs" class="page-section hidden py-12">
                           <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-center uppercase tracking-wider">Environmental, Health & Safety</h2>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-10">
                             <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                                <img src="images/EHS_1.avif" alt="EHS Article" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                                <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-red-700 mb-2">EHS</span>
                                <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">The Rise of Mycelium Packaging: Can Fungus Replace Plastic?</h4>
                                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">Startups are attracting major investment for their biodegradable materials...</p>
                                <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                                <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                    <span class="article-author">Jane Doe</span>
                                    <span class="article-date">September 26, 2025</span>
                                    <span class="article-author-img">images/author-jane.jpg</span>
                                </div>
                                   <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                    <p>The world is drowning in plastic, and innovators are looking to nature for a solution. Enter mycelium, the root network of fungi. This remarkable biological material can be grown into custom shapes, creating packaging that is 100% biodegradable and compostable.</p>
                                    <p>Companies like Ecovative Design are pioneering this technology, mixing agricultural waste like hemp hurds with mycelium, which then grows to form a solid, lightweight, and surprisingly durable material. It can replace Styrofoam, plastics, and other harmful packaging materials.</p>
                                    <blockquote>"Nature has already figured out how to create high-performance materials. We just need to learn how to work with it."</blockquote>
                                    <p>While challenges in scaling production and cost remain, mycelium represents a paradigm shift in our approach to materials science. It's not just about creating a less harmful product; it's about creating products that are actively beneficial to the environment when their lifecycle ends.</p>
                                </div>
                            </article>
                             <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                                <img src="images/EHS_2.avif" alt="EHS Article 2" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                                <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-emerald-700 mb-2">EHS</span>
                                <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Carbon Capture's New Frontier: Direct Air Capture Facilities Go Global</h4>
                                <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">New facilities in Iceland and Oman are proving that sucking CO2 directly from the air is a scalable climate solution.</p>
                                <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                                <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                    <span class="article-author">Devansh Singh Rawal</span>
                                    <span class="article-date">September 21, 2025</span>
                                    <span class="article-author-img">images/author-devansh.jpg</span>
                                </div>
                                   <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                    <p>For years, carbon capture has focused on trapping emissions at the source, like power plants. But a more ambitious technology is gaining traction: Direct Air Capture (DAC). DAC facilities use giant fans and chemical processes to pull existing CO2 directly out of the atmosphere.</p>
                                    <p>Pioneering projects, like Climeworks' "Orca" plant in Iceland, are already operational. The captured CO2 is then injected deep underground, where it mineralizes and turns to stone, permanently removing it from the carbon cycle. New, larger facilities are now being planned in locations from Texas to Oman.</p>
                                    <blockquote>"Reducing emissions is paramount, but it's not enough. We also need to clean up the carbon we've already put into the air. DAC is a critical tool for that."</blockquote>
                                    <p>The technology is energy-intensive and currently very expensive, but costs are falling rapidly as the technology scales. Proponents see DAC not as a silver bullet, but as an essential component in the portfolio of solutions needed to combat climate change and achieve net-zero emissions.</p>
                                </div>
                            </article>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- Science Page Section -->
                <section id="page-science" class="page-section hidden py-12">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-center uppercase tracking-wider">Science</h2>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-10">
                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1532187863486-abf9dbad1b69?q=80&w=1974&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Science Article" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-sky-700 mb-2">Science</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Gene-Edited Crops: A Solution to Food Scarcity?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">With CRISPR-Cas9 technology, scientists are developing drought-resistant wheat and rice...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Devansh Singh Rawal</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 25, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-devansh.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>The specter of climate change and a growing global population poses a dire threat to food security. Scientists, however, believe they have a powerful tool in their arsenal: CRISPR-Cas9 gene editing.</p>
                                <p>Unlike traditional GMOs, which often introduce genes from other species, CRISPR allows for precise edits to a plant's own DNA. This can be used to enhance desirable traits, such as making wheat resistant to drought, rice more nutritious, or tomatoes less susceptible to disease. The process mimics natural genetic mutation but on an accelerated timescale.</p>
                                <blockquote>"We can now do in months what used to take decades of selective breeding. This technology is crucial for adapting our agriculture to a rapidly changing world."</blockquote>
                                <p>Regulatory hurdles and public perception remain significant challenges. However, many scientists argue that the potential benefits—feeding more people with fewer resources—are too great to ignore. The debate over gene-edited crops will be one of the defining scientific conversations of our time.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                           <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1579154341147-48242851752b?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Science Article 2" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-violet-700 mb-2">Science</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Lab-Grown Lungs Successfully Transplanted in Animal Trials</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">A major milestone in regenerative medicine could eliminate transplant waiting lists...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Jane Doe</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 20, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-jane.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>For patients with end-stage lung disease, a transplant is often the only hope. But a shortage of donor organs and the risk of immune rejection make it a fraught process. Now, a breakthrough in regenerative medicine offers a glimpse of a future without waiting lists.</p>
                                <p>Researchers have successfully grown functional lungs in a laboratory using a patient's own cells and transplanted them into pigs. The process involves taking a donor lung, stripping it of its cells to leave a protein "scaffold," and then reseeding that scaffold with the recipient's own stem cells. The lung is then grown in a bioreactor that mimics the conditions of the body.</p>
                                <blockquote>"This is a major step toward creating bioengineered organs for human patients. The goal is to one day create custom-made replacement organs on demand."</blockquote>
                                <p>The transplanted lungs functioned well in the animal subjects for several weeks. While human trials are still years away, this research represents a landmark achievement and a profound source of hope for millions.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- Tech Page Section -->
                <section id="page-tech" class="page-section hidden py-12">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-center uppercase tracking-wider">Technology</h2>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-10">
                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519389950473-47ba0277781c?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Tech Article" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-green-700 mb-2">Tech</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Post-Quantum Encryption is Here: Is Your Data Truly Safe?</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">The first NIST-approved quantum-resistant algorithms are being deployed...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">John Smith</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 24, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-john.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>The digital world runs on encryption, but a new threat looms on the horizon: quantum computers. These powerful machines, once theoretical, are becoming a reality, and they possess the ability to break the encryption standards that protect everything from your bank account to national secrets.</p>
                                <p>In response, a global effort has been underway to develop "post-quantum cryptography" (PQC)—new encryption algorithms that are resistant to attacks from both classical and quantum computers. The U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) has recently standardized the first suite of these PQC algorithms.</p>
                                <blockquote>"The transition to quantum-resistant encryption is one of the most critical cybersecurity upgrades in the history of the internet. It's a race against time."</blockquote>
                                <p>Companies and governments are now beginning the monumental task of upgrading their systems. For the average user, the change will be invisible, but behind the scenes, it's a critical defense against the looming threat of "Q-Day"—the day a quantum computer can shatter our digital security.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1677756119517-756a188d2278?q=80&w=1974&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="Tech Article 2" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-amber-700 mb-2">Tech</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">Who Owns AI-Generated Art? The Legal Battles Begin</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">As AI-created music and visuals become indistinguishable from human work, courts are facing landmark cases...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Devansh Singh Rawal</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 19, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-devansh.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>A song generated by an AI in the style of a famous artist tops the charts. A stunning digital painting created with a text prompt wins an art competition. These scenarios are no longer hypothetical, and they've thrown copyright law into a state of chaos.</p>
                                <p>The central question is: can a work created by a non-human entity be copyrighted? The U.S. Copyright Office has stated that works must have human authorship to qualify. But what is the threshold for human involvement? Is writing a detailed prompt enough to be considered the "author"?</p>
                                <blockquote>"We are grappling with foundational questions about creativity and authorship. The law, as it's currently written, is simply not equipped to handle this new reality."</blockquote>
                                <p>Artists are concerned about their styles being replicated without consent, while tech companies argue that AI is merely a tool, like a camera or a paintbrush. The outcomes of these early legal battles will set precedents that could redefine the creative industries for decades to come.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <!-- Commerce Page Section -->
                <section id="page-commerce" class="page-section hidden py-12">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8 text-center uppercase tracking-wider">Commerce</h2>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-10">
                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1556740738-b6a63e2775d2?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="commerce Article" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-cyan-700 mb-2">Commerce</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">The Future of Supply Chains is Hyper-Localized</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">On-demand manufacturing and 3D printing are disrupting global trade patterns...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">John Smith</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 18, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-john.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>The pandemic and geopolitical tensions have exposed the fragility of global supply chains. The era of relying on a single factory halfway across the world is coming to an end. The future, many experts believe, is hyper-localized.</p>
                                <p>Technologies like advanced automation, robotics, and 3D printing are making it economically viable to produce goods closer to the point of consumption. This "reshoring" or "near-shoring" trend is being driven by a desire for resilience, speed, and sustainability. Instead of massive container ships, think local micro-factories that can produce customized goods on demand.</p>
                                <blockquote>"The supply chain of tomorrow isn't a chain at all; it's a network. It's decentralized, adaptable, and far more resilient to global shocks."</blockquote>
                                <p>This shift has profound implications for global trade, manufacturing jobs, and carbon emissions. While global trade won't disappear, it will be transformed, with a greater emphasis on regional self-sufficiency and technologically advanced manufacturing.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                        <article class="article-card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md hover:shadow-xl hover:scale-105 hover:-translate-y-1 transition-all duration-300 flex flex-col">
                            <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1642138257544-75b9f708a3d4?q=80&w=2070&auto=format&fit=crop" alt="commerce Article 2" class="rounded-md mb-4 w-full h-48 object-cover">
                            <span class="article-category text-xs font-bold uppercase text-lime-700 mb-2">Commerce</span>
                            <h4 class="article-title text-xl font-bold mb-2 flex-grow">The Tokenization of Real-World Assets</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-4">Blockchain is moving beyond cryptocurrency to transform ownership of physical goods...</p>
                            <a href="#" class="read-more-btn font-bold text-sm text-gray-800 hover:underline mt-auto">Continue Reading &rarr;</a>
                            <div class="article-meta hidden">
                                <span class="article-author">Jane Doe</span>
                                <span class="article-date">September 17, 2025</span>
                                <span class="article-author-img">images/author-jane.jpg</span>
                            </div>
                               <div class="article-full-content hidden">
                                <p>For most people, blockchain means Bitcoin. But the underlying technology is poised to revolutionize commerce in a far more profound way through the tokenization of real-world assets (RWAs).</p>
                                <p>Tokenization is the process of creating a digital representation—a token—of a physical or financial asset on a blockchain. This could be a piece of real estate, a fine art painting, or even a share in a private company. By tokenizing an asset, it can be easily divided, traded, and owned fractionally.</p>
                                <blockquote>"We are unlocking trillions of dollars in illiquid assets. Soon, you'll be able to buy a fraction of a skyscraper as easily as you buy a stock."</blockquote>
                                <p>This opens up investment opportunities to a much broader audience and creates new sources of liquidity for asset owners. While regulatory frameworks are still evolving, the tokenization of RWAs represents a major step toward a more efficient, transparent, and democratized financial system.</p>
                            </div>
                        </article>
                    </div>
                </section>

